it would be a quote from my favorite review

248
00:15:06,306 --> 00:15:09,508
of one of Chris's products.

249
00:15:11,828 --> 00:15:15,650
I don't think that would be a quote for one of John's products.

250
00:15:15,650 --> 00:15:18,371
Normally you would think of it as a quote for one of John's products.

251
00:15:18,371 --> 00:15:21,273
But long, long ago in the bad blood days,

252
00:15:21,273 --> 00:15:25,415
one of our reviewers took exception of one of those skinks-like puzzles

253
00:15:25,415 --> 00:15:30,157
where in this case you had to kill this little turtle-like creature

254
00:15:30,157 --> 00:15:33,839
and get the blood out of it vampirically in order to survive.

255
00:15:33,839 --> 00:15:37,821
And I guess this was the nascent animal activist in Charles

256
00:15:37,821 --> 00:15:40,122
and he thought it was morally reprehensible.

257
00:15:40,646 --> 00:15:45,574
And I know the folks at Origin were quite upset at us for a long time over that review.

258
00:15:45,574 --> 00:15:50,002
But I want to talk to you about some of the more exciting things.

259
00:15:50,002 --> 00:15:50,723
For example...

260
00:15:51,855 --> 00:15:57,000
I remember when you first came over from England and you were working on Times of Lore and

261
00:15:57,000 --> 00:16:01,904
Richard was trying to describe the Times of Lore interface to us and he was all excited

262
00:16:01,904 --> 00:16:07,109
and he made the mistake of calling it a Nintendo-like interface and saying that we're changing everything

263
00:16:07,109 --> 00:16:12,534
to that, you know, and it just, you know, panicked those of us who equated the Nintendo

264
00:16:12,534 --> 00:16:16,457
style game with being shallower than the PC game.

265
00:16:16,935 --> 00:16:21,576
And yet, when we saw the game, it was extremely deep,

266
00:16:21,576 --> 00:16:22,497
and it surprised us.

267
00:16:22,497 --> 00:16:26,018
And we did notice that the influence went

268
00:16:26,018 --> 00:16:28,019
on toward iconic interfaces.

269
00:16:28,019 --> 00:16:31,740
What do you think the most important contribution,

270
00:16:31,740 --> 00:16:34,021
whether it was in interface, or whether it

271
00:16:34,021 --> 00:16:37,882
was an interactive sound, or whether it was in object

272
00:16:37,882 --> 00:16:41,364
definition in games, what is the most important contribution

273
00:16:41,364 --> 00:16:42,964
in all your tenure at Origin, do you think?

274
00:16:42,964 --> 00:16:45,445
Well, I mean, I

275
00:16:45,792 --> 00:16:50,874
The biggest thing I always try and do in everything I do is I want to immerse the player in the

276
00:16:50,874 --> 00:16:56,975
environment and so I think that what I'm proudest of with Wing Commander, what I've done in

277
00:16:56,975 --> 00:17:00,656
the past, is any time that I sort of remove the feeling of interface.

278
00:17:00,656 --> 00:17:05,258
So, you know, like when it's in Wing Commander instead of, you know, you going over and going

279
00:17:05,258 --> 00:17:10,179
on file and save, you click on a bunk bed to save or you, you know, click on the airlock

280
00:17:10,179 --> 00:17:11,979
door to exit the game.

281
00:17:11,979 --> 00:17:15,340
And I mean I guess the coolest thing from my standpoint is...

282
00:17:15,902 --> 00:17:19,326
from putting it into something like Wing Commander and then

283
00:17:19,326 --> 00:17:23,650
seeing that sort of graphical immersive interface sort of

284
00:17:23,650 --> 00:17:26,994
permutate other people's games, which is kind of cool.

285
00:17:26,994 --> 00:17:28,836
But I mean, that's for me.

286
00:17:28,836 --> 00:17:30,898
All I want to do is I want to build an experience that I get

287
00:17:30,898 --> 00:17:33,861
lost in the world for two hours, 20 hours, 40 hours, and

288
00:17:33,861 --> 00:17:35,823
have a good time.

289
00:17:35,823 --> 00:17:37,845
And so I guess that's what I like the most.

290
00:17:39,482 --> 00:17:46,908
I think your contributions to interface have been very important because I've seen it across, you know, lots of different game companies.

291
00:17:46,908 --> 00:17:51,412
Just like John's contributions to interface have been very, very important at a later period.

292
00:17:51,412 --> 00:17:57,036
There was one thing that you tried in Wing Commander, the first Wing Commander, I thought was extremely important.

293
00:17:57,692 --> 00:17:59,913
and extremely significant.

294
00:17:59,913 --> 00:18:02,234
And yet it turned out that when the gamers got hold of it,

295
00:18:02,234 --> 00:18:05,736
it was something of a failure.

296
00:18:05,736 --> 00:18:07,916
What were some of the reactions that you got from people

297
00:18:07,916 --> 00:18:10,137
about the losing track in Wing Commander?

298
00:18:10,137 --> 00:18:15,299
Well, I mean, the funny thing with interactive fiction

299
00:18:15,299 --> 00:18:18,921
is that you have to give everybody choices

300
00:18:18,921 --> 00:18:22,462
so they don't feel like they're constrained to any one path.

301
00:18:22,462 --> 00:18:26,384
But the problem is that you spend, say, 50% of your time

302
00:18:26,981 --> 00:18:29,522
on the paths that aren't the optimum paths in the game.

303
00:18:29,522 --> 00:18:31,582
And then at the end of the day, you're there going, hey, did

304
00:18:31,582 --> 00:18:32,582
you play down this track?

305
00:18:32,582 --> 00:18:33,422
Did you do this?

306
00:18:33,422 --> 00:18:34,203
Did you do this?

307
00:18:34,203 --> 00:18:35,823
And everyone's like, no, I didn't.

308
00:18:35,823 --> 00:18:38,424
And you're like, I just spent a year on that.

309
00:18:38,424 --> 00:18:38,924
What's the deal?

310
00:18:38,924 --> 00:18:42,725
And I think that it really came home to me when I was

311
00:18:42,725 --> 00:18:45,425
sitting and I was talking to one of the dynamics guys about

312
00:18:45,425 --> 00:18:46,385
The Rise of the Dragon.

313
00:18:46,385 --> 00:18:47,886
And I was saying, yeah, I really loved it.

314
00:18:47,886 --> 00:18:49,466
I played it all the way through.

315
00:18:49,466 --> 00:18:50,867
And I did this, and I did this.

316
00:18:50,867 --> 00:18:52,487
And he's like, oh, did you go to this level?

317
00:18:52,487 --> 00:18:53,167
And did you do this?

318
00:18:53,167 --> 00:18:54,507
And did you meet this character?

319
00:18:54,507 --> 00:18:55,708
And I was like, no.

320
00:18:55,708 --> 00:18:56,368
And he's like.

321
00:18:56,674 --> 00:18:58,015
And he was heartbroken.

322
00:18:58,015 --> 00:19:01,638
So I guess it's one of those necessary evils, because you

323
00:19:01,638 --> 00:19:04,520
have to do it so you feel like you have a choice, and you

324
00:19:04,520 --> 00:19:09,304
feel like the world reacts to what you do.

325
00:19:09,304 --> 00:19:11,966
But you're also sitting there working on it, going, well, I

326
00:19:11,966 --> 00:19:14,628
know about 50% or 60% of people aren't actually ever

327
00:19:14,628 --> 00:19:17,811
going to experience this.

328
00:19:17,811 --> 00:19:18,191
And I don't know.

329
00:19:18,191 --> 00:19:20,233
I guess you need to do it so everyone feels happy about

330
00:19:20,233 --> 00:19:21,794
they've gone the losing track.

331
00:19:21,794 --> 00:19:23,516
They haven't gone the losing track, that is.

332
00:19:23,516 --> 00:19:25,337
So necessary evil.

333
00:19:25,918 --> 00:19:28,500
right but it seems like you shortened the losing track in

334
00:19:28,500 --> 00:19:30,801
progressively aggressively

335
00:19:30,801 --> 00:19:34,243
and of course with uh... filming that made it uh... very necessary

336
00:19:34,243 --> 00:19:39,927
the great thing about the wing commander series uh... i thought was that it it

337
00:19:39,927 --> 00:19:42,069
pushed upgrades at every new release of uh... you know

338
00:19:42,069 --> 00:19:48,433
that is good uh... you know when you're in a magazine that's advertising driven

339
00:19:48,433 --> 00:19:48,973
you know

340
00:19:51,320 --> 00:19:55,243
But it's also good for the whole industry as a whole because people have a tendency

341
00:19:55,243 --> 00:19:59,967
to buy more games when they buy new equipment because they want to find stuff that shows

342
00:19:59,967 --> 00:20:06,912
it off. And certainly in the era of the Wing Commanders, the Wing Commanders showed off

343
00:20:06,912 --> 00:20:13,897
new sound cards with Wing Commander 2. They certainly showed off new graphics cards with

344
00:20:13,897 --> 00:20:18,961
Wing Commander 3, which is one of the few FMV games that's ever spoken well of.

345
00:20:20,155 --> 00:20:22,876
And they showed Electronic Arts how to spend lots of money

346
00:20:22,876 --> 00:20:23,516
in Wink-Man 4.

347
00:20:23,516 --> 00:20:23,856
Oh, wow.

348
00:20:23,856 --> 00:20:33,199
I mean, I will say that the process that got me there

349
00:20:33,199 --> 00:20:34,219
is a long time ago.

350
00:20:34,219 --> 00:20:36,820
You mentioned Bad Blood and Times of the Law.

351
00:20:36,820 --> 00:20:38,141
So I came from England, and I was

352
00:20:38,141 --> 00:20:40,481
used to programming on Commodore 64.

353
00:20:40,481 --> 00:20:43,242
And back in those days in England, it was tape drive.

354
00:20:43,242 --> 00:20:44,362
There was no disk drive.

355
00:20:44,362 --> 00:20:46,603
So I was really proud about Times of the Law

356
00:20:46,603 --> 00:20:47,823
because everything fit in 64K.

357
00:20:48,548 --> 00:20:51,330
And there was this huge world and you ventured around.

358
00:20:51,330 --> 00:20:54,731
And the game came out, and it came out over here.

359
00:20:54,731 --> 00:20:57,793
And people didn't go, oh, well, it's really great because it

360
00:20:57,793 --> 00:20:58,633
can fit in 64K.

361
00:20:58,633 --> 00:21:02,115
They went, well, it's cool and everything, but I'm playing

362
00:21:02,115 --> 00:21:03,716
this other game, and it comes on four disks.

363
00:21:03,716 --> 00:21:05,577
And it doesn't have as much of it.

364
00:21:05,577 --> 00:21:08,778
And I was sitting there going, hmm, I don't know about that.

365
00:21:08,778 --> 00:21:10,459
And about the same time, MicroProse came out with F19.

366
00:21:10,459 --> 00:21:12,260
I remember going up to MicroProse because they

367
00:21:12,260 --> 00:21:14,741
distributed our stuff over in Europe.

368
00:21:15,430 --> 00:21:16,531
And they were showing me F19.

369
00:21:16,531 --> 00:21:19,093
And I was like, man, this is the most incredible 3D

370
00:21:19,093 --> 00:21:21,074
simulation I've ever seen.

371
00:21:21,074 --> 00:21:23,976
Too bad it only runs at four frames a second on a 38625,

372
00:21:23,976 --> 00:21:26,557
which back then was like a $10,000 machine.

373
00:21:26,557 --> 00:21:29,079
No one's ever going to be impressed or like this, because

374
00:21:29,079 --> 00:21:30,540
no one's got this machine.

375
00:21:30,540 --> 00:21:32,621
And it comes out, and it's absolutely huge here.

376
00:21:32,621 --> 00:21:36,884
And I'm sitting there, and I'm going, hmm, well, I guess

377
00:21:36,884 --> 00:21:39,125
there's a reason not to compromise and everything.

378
00:21:39,125 --> 00:21:42,367
So that's really what happened with Wing Commander.

379
00:21:42,367 --> 00:21:44,108
I said, OK, well, screw it.

380
00:21:44,547 --> 00:21:49,190
I'm going to use every single opportunity and tool I can get on the maximum available

381
00:21:49,190 --> 00:21:56,073
hardware right now to make the gaming experience as good as possible because my personal belief

382
00:21:56,073 --> 00:21:58,895
is that people aren't very objective about it.

383
00:21:58,895 --> 00:21:59,776
They're subjective.

384
00:21:59,776 --> 00:22:01,657
They go, is this the best game I've seen?

385
00:22:01,657 --> 00:22:04,898
And they don't go, oh, is this the best game I've seen that runs in 128K?

386
00:22:04,898 --> 00:22:06,759
Or is this the best game I've seen in CGA?

387
00:22:06,759 --> 00:22:09,161
They just go, is this the best game I've seen?

388
00:22:09,161 --> 00:22:13,023
So after I sort of made that decision point in Wing Commander onwards was...

389
00:22:13,359 --> 00:22:18,082
very much driven by, OK, let's make the best game possible,

390
00:22:18,082 --> 00:22:19,583
no holds barred from there on.

391
00:22:19,583 --> 00:22:21,784
Luckily, it seemed to work out.

392
00:22:22,803 --> 00:22:25,886
In the creative process, as you were going from Times of War,

393
00:22:25,886 --> 00:22:29,369
which you basically wrote virtually all yourself,

394
00:22:29,369 --> 00:22:32,471
to Bad Blood, which you must have split off

395
00:22:32,471 --> 00:22:35,154
some of the programming on to the Wing Commander series,

396
00:22:35,154 --> 00:22:38,156
where more and more things were being done by other people.

397
00:22:38,156 --> 00:22:43,161
Can you describe for a little bit how your role changed

398
00:22:43,161 --> 00:22:44,582
from game to game?

399
00:22:44,582 --> 00:22:47,224
And is starting your own company some desire

400
00:22:47,224 --> 00:22:49,346
to get back more hands on yourself?

401
00:22:50,731 --> 00:22:52,571
Well, I mean, I think it is a design.

402
00:22:52,571 --> 00:22:57,033
I mean, actually, the one sad thing about game development

403
00:22:57,033 --> 00:22:59,214
nowadays is that in the old days, you could do everything

404
00:22:59,214 --> 00:23:02,915
yourself, and you could totally control the look, the

405
00:23:02,915 --> 00:23:03,295
feel, the sound.

406
00:23:03,295 --> 00:23:05,135
You do the writing, you do the programming, you do the

407
00:23:05,135 --> 00:23:06,236
artwork, you do the sound.

408
00:23:06,236 --> 00:23:09,117
And it could be a one-man affair, and it could be an

409
00:23:09,117 --> 00:23:10,957
absolute single vision.

410
00:23:10,957 --> 00:23:14,018
And now, because of what everybody expects in terms of

411
00:23:14,018 --> 00:23:16,479
the quality of the product, you just can't afford to do

412
00:23:16,479 --> 00:23:17,539
that, I mean, it would take you.

413
00:23:17,917 --> 00:23:20,578
20 years and by the time it came out it would be old technology.

414
00:23:20,578 --> 00:23:25,722
And so, you know, the sad thing is that you don't get to have that 100% level of control

415
00:23:25,722 --> 00:23:26,302
over the product.

416
00:23:26,302 --> 00:23:30,685
I mean, the good thing is that you get to work with a lot of other really talented people

417
00:23:30,685 --> 00:23:34,488
and they, you know, in a lot of ways make your work better.

418
00:23:34,488 --> 00:23:39,871
So I mean, I guess at the end of the day my role sort of moves more to being creative

419
00:23:39,871 --> 00:23:44,214
shepherd and sort of evangelist of exactly how it's going to work and, you know, more

420
00:23:44,214 --> 00:23:47,557
away from the actual technician that's building all the building blocks of it.

421
00:23:48,048 --> 00:23:52,849
And I guess what I tried doing with Digital Anvil is I have

422
00:23:52,849 --> 00:23:55,250
felt a little bit recently that in the huge industry

423
00:23:55,250 --> 00:23:59,031
expansion that it's kind of gotten away from a little bit

424
00:23:59,031 --> 00:24:01,832
of that sort of core vision on how products are built.

425
00:24:01,832 --> 00:24:05,773
And so what I'm trying to do with Digital Anvil is have a

426
00:24:05,773 --> 00:24:08,654
company that focuses on building great products, has

427
00:24:08,654 --> 00:24:12,655
less people on the teams, and allows the team the time they

428
00:24:12,655 --> 00:24:14,656
need to do the product and gives them the support they

429
00:24:14,656 --> 00:24:16,316
need to do it.

430
00:24:16,316 --> 00:24:17,677
So we'll see if it works.

431
00:24:17,677 --> 00:24:17,797
But.

432
00:24:18,386 --> 00:24:19,187
I mean, it's a good theory.

433
00:24:19,187 --> 00:24:21,388
It's something that me and a bunch of my peer group

434
00:24:21,388 --> 00:24:23,730
have been talking about for a long time.

435
00:24:23,730 --> 00:24:25,111
And we figured, OK, time to put a push it up.

436
00:24:25,111 --> 00:24:27,713
Well, I'm pretty excited about what you told me

437
00:24:27,713 --> 00:24:29,254
about the new project.

438
00:24:29,254 --> 00:24:30,895
And we're going to come back to it later

439
00:24:30,895 --> 00:24:34,418
and let you talk as much as you feel like you can about that.

440
00:24:34,418 --> 00:24:37,100
We want to move on to John here.

441
00:24:37,100 --> 00:24:45,106
I don't know how many people know, but John was at origin

442
00:24:45,106 --> 00:24:47,908
and worked with Chuck on 2400 AD.

443
00:24:47,908 --> 00:24:48,228
And

444
00:24:49,240 --> 00:24:54,802
and moved over. And actually, you know, Chris Roberts stole the idea of Wing Commander from

445
00:24:54,802 --> 00:24:59,504
Paul Neurath and John when they did Space Rogue, which was sort of, you know, Wing Commander

446
00:24:59,504 --> 00:25:07,307
with tunnels. But anyway, then John moved from there to Softdisk Corporation where he

447
00:25:07,307 --> 00:25:13,030
was virtually doing a product, like a product of the month, weren't you, with Softdisk?

448
00:25:13,030 --> 00:25:17,312
Every month. We had to, well, I started out...

449
00:25:18,563 --> 00:25:28,469
After I left Origin, which was in June of 88, I got there to work on the, was it, Apple II to Commodore 64 port of 2400 AD.

450
00:25:28,469 --> 00:25:32,411
And while I was working on that, Paul Neuron...

451
00:25:32,411 --> 00:25:39,096
So you reviewed the Apple II version and that one was cancelled, right?

452
00:25:39,096 --> 00:25:43,018
No, well, no, the Apple II version came out. I don't know how many copies it sold.

453
00:25:43,018 --> 00:25:45,860
It was a, I liked it, it was a fun game.

454
00:25:46,942 --> 00:25:49,663
So I was doing my very first Commodore programming,

455
00:25:49,663 --> 00:25:52,965
converting the Apple II version of 2400 AD

456
00:25:52,965 --> 00:25:56,527
to the Commodore 64, which I had to learn pretty quickly.

457
00:25:56,527 --> 00:26:01,590
And it was probably three months through the conversion

458
00:26:01,590 --> 00:26:04,871
when Paul Neroff really needed some help on Space Road.

459
00:26:04,871 --> 00:26:08,253
And because he had to get the game done,

460
00:26:08,253 --> 00:26:09,594
it had been going on too long.

461
00:26:09,594 --> 00:26:13,196
So I was there to do the NPC code for him.

462
00:26:13,196 --> 00:26:14,216
It ended up that.

463
00:26:15,020 --> 00:26:23,503
He actually didn't use my code in the game because I left pretty soon after that to kind of co-found another company.

464
00:26:23,503 --> 00:26:27,704
And he ended up getting someone else to program the NPC stuff.

465
00:26:27,704 --> 00:26:37,008
But when I went on to the next company, it was a conversion house called Inside Out Software just down the road from Origin in New Hampshire.

466
00:26:37,008 --> 00:26:44,230
And I worked on the Might and Magic 2 conversion of the Commodore 64, and I worked on various other ports.

467
00:26:44,230 --> 00:26:44,530
And...

468
00:26:45,833 --> 00:26:51,536
And I finally decided to leave Inside Out to go to Softdisk because it was an Apple II.

469
00:26:51,536 --> 00:26:55,318
It was an Apple II magazine, but it also did PC work.

470
00:26:55,318 --> 00:27:00,541
And this was in 1988 where the Apple II market was really dying hard.

471
00:27:00,541 --> 00:27:05,824
And I needed to actually learn the PC because it was the market.

472
00:27:05,824 --> 00:27:09,045
So I just called up the president of the company.

473
00:27:09,045 --> 00:27:12,227
I told him who I was and what I had worked on and stuff.

474
00:27:12,935 --> 00:27:14,875
I told him I didn't know anything about the PC at all,

475
00:27:14,875 --> 00:27:16,496
but I really want to learn how to program it.

476
00:27:16,496 --> 00:27:18,456
And he's like, come on down.

477
00:27:18,456 --> 00:27:21,277
So that was really cool that he let me come down

478
00:27:21,277 --> 00:27:23,898
and just learn how to program the PC,

479
00:27:23,898 --> 00:27:25,919
knowing nothing about it.

480
00:27:25,919 --> 00:27:27,779
And while I was at Softdisk,

481
00:27:27,779 --> 00:27:30,720
I was doing utility work

482
00:27:30,720 --> 00:27:33,841
and some of my games I was porting to the PC,

483
00:27:33,841 --> 00:27:37,562
and I had to get something done every single month.

484
00:27:37,562 --> 00:27:41,523
And about a year and three months after...

